# Cursor AI Rules for DES166 AI Assistant Project

## Project Context
This is a Next.js 14 project using TypeScript, React, and Tailwind CSS.
It's an AI-powered FAQ system for a UW design course (DES166).

## Tech Stack
- Framework: Next.js 14 (App Router)
- Language: TypeScript
- Styling: Tailwind CSS
- AI: OpenAI GPT-4o-mini
- Deployment: Vercel

## Code Style Preferences
- Use TypeScript for all new files
- Use functional components with hooks
- Prefer arrow functions
- Use Tailwind CSS for styling (no CSS modules)
- Follow Next.js 14 app router conventions
- Use "use client" directive for client components
- Keep components small and focused

## File Organization
- Components go in /components
- API routes in /app/api
- Data/constants in /data
- Utility functions in /lib
- Types can be colocated or in separate .types.ts files

## Naming Conventions
- Components: PascalCase (e.g., ChatInterface.tsx)
- Files: kebab-case for non-components (e.g., qa-data.ts)
- Functions: camelCase
- Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
- CSS classes: Tailwind utilities only

## Important Notes
- Always include error handling in API routes
- Use proper TypeScript types (avoid 'any')
- Keep API key in environment variables
- Test components with various screen sizes
- Consider accessibility (ARIA labels, keyboard nav)

## Common Patterns in This Project

### Adding a new QA item:
```typescript
{
  id: number,
  category: "application" | "portfolio" | "major" | "grade" | "advising" | "project",
  question: string,
  answer: string,
  links?: string[],
  keywords?: string[],
}
```

### Creating a new component:
```typescript
"use client"; // if needed

import { useState } from "react";

export default function ComponentName() {
  // Component logic
  return (
    <div className="tailwind-classes">
      {/* JSX */}
    </div>
